s]]\n[[Category:Secondary education-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of school-related attacks|secondary]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nThis is a '''list of attacks related to secondary schools''' that have occurred around the world. These are attacks that have occurred on school property or related primarily to school issues or events. A narrow definition of the word ''attacks'' is used for this list so as to exclude warfare, robberies, gang violence, public attacks (as in political protests), accidental shootings, and [[suicide]]s and [[murder\u2013suicide]]s by rejected spouses or suitors. Incidents that involved only staff who work at the school have been classified as belonging at [[List of rampage killers|List of workplace killings]]. It also excludes events where no injuries take place, if an attack is foiled.\n\nThe listed attacks include [[shooting]]s, [[stabbing]]s, [[Cutting|slashings]], [[bombing]]s, and [[Battery (crime)|beatings]] administered with [[blunt instrument]]s.\n\n==Secondary school incidents==\n\n===1850s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| November 2, 1853\n| [[Louisville, Kentucky]], United States\n| Matthew Ward\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n| A student, Matthew Ward, went to school and shot and killed Schoolmaster Mr. Butler for excessively punishing his brother the day before. He was acquitted.<ref>April 29, 1854,'' The New York Times''</ref>\n|-\n|July 6, 1858\n|[[Baltimore, Maryland]], United States\n|\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|The 15yr old son of Col. John T. Farlow (Baltimore's Marshal of Police 1867-70), was shot to death during a [[Sunday school|Sabbath School]] gathering. The shooter escaped, but several arrests were made.<ref>''Evening Star,'' Washington D.C., July 06, 1858</ref>\n|}\n\n===1860s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n|January 21, 1860\n|[[Todd County, Kentucky]], United States\n|\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|A son of Col. Elijah Sebree was shot dead by another student.<ref>''The Penny Press.'', Cincinnati, OH, January 21, 1860</ref>\n|-\n|April 2, 1867\n|[[Madison, Florida]], United States\n|Frank Pope\n| align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|Frank Pope, a pupil at the St. John's seminary, shot and killed his teacher Mr. Bristow with a pistol.<ref>''Memphis Daily Appeal'', April 09, 1867</ref>\n|}\n\n===1870s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| February 1, 1872\n|[[Washington, Pennsylvania]], United States\n| Thomas McGiffen\n|\n|align=\"center\"|1\n| At the all-girls Union School, Thomas McGiffen, the 17-year-old son of Col. Norton McGiffin and brother of naval hero [[Philo McGiffin]], shot and seriously wounded the principal, Prof. Wilson, because the professor refused to deliver a note to a young lady for him.<ref>''The Sun,'' New York City, February 02, 1872</ref>\n|-\n|February 20, 1874\n|[[Agency, Montana]], United States\n|Thomas Sguires, 20\n| align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|After being ejected from school for disobedience, Thomas Sguires, 20 years old, returned to the school yard a day or two later, and fatally shot Prof. Hayes three times.<ref>''Nebraska Advertiser'', February 26, 1874</ref>\n|-\n|May 24, 1879\n|[[Lancaster, New York]], United States\n| Frank Shugart\n| \n| align=\"center\"|1\n|Frank Shugart, a [[telegraph operator]], shot and severely injured Mr. Carr, superintendent of the stables at a girls' school.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1879/05/26/archives/shot-by-a-telegraph-operator.html|work=The New York Times|title=Shot by a Telegraph Operator|date=May 26, 1879}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===1880s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| January 21, 1882\n| [[Red Bud, Illinois]], United States\n| James E. McBride, 17\n| align=\"center\"|1\n| \n| After striking student James McBride in the face, teacher Robert Bailey was fatally wounded in a scuffle, in which the student stabbed him twice with a knife he was using to sharpen a pencil.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1882/01/22/archives/a-teacher-stabbed-by-a-pupil.html A teacher stabbed by a pupil], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (January 22, 1882)</ref>\n|-\n| April 13, 1882\n| [[Huntsville, Texas]], United States\n| G. W. Gray\n|\n|align=\"center\"| 1\n| G. W. Gray, a student at the [[Sam Houston]] Normal School, shot and wounded another student, M. J. Jordan.  They were arguing over a comic valentine.<ref>''The Milan Exchange''(Milan, Tenn.), April 15, 1882</ref>\n|-\n| August 27, 1886\n| [[Charleston, West Virginia]], United States\n| John Griffith, 15\n|\n| align=\"center\"|1\n| After being reprimanded by his teacher, James Kiser, 15-year-old John Griffith, a student at a school in Jackson County, brought a knife and rocks to school the next morning. A struggle ensued in which student Griffith stabbed Kiser several times.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1886/08/29/archives/stabbed-by-a-pupil.html Stabbed by a pupil], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (August 29, 1886)</ref>\n|-\n| June 29, 1888\n| [[Dalby, Queensland]], Australia\n| Peterson\n| align=\"center\"|1\n|\n| A 12-year-old student named Peterson stabbed his teacher when he was chastised for chasing another boy with a knife.<ref>[http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/3479157 A school teacher stabbed], ''[[The Brisbane Courier]]'' (June 30, 1888)</ref>\n|}\n\n===1890s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| March 26, 1893\n|[[Plain Dealing, Louisiana]], United States\n|\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|align=\"center\"|1\n| During an evening school dance at Plain Dealing High School, a fight broke out. Two youths were shot dead, two more were fatally wounded, and the high school's Professor Johnson was shot in the arm.<ref>''San Francisco Call,'' Volume 73, Number 117, 27 March 1893</ref>\n|-\n| January 26, 1899\n| [[Albany, Missouri]], United States\n| Charles Ayres\n| align=\"center\"|1\n|\n| When he got whipped by his teacher T. B. Hunter, 13-year-old student Charles Ayres drew a jackknife and slashed the teacher's throat.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1899/01/27/archives/schoolboy-stabs-a-teacher-jackknife-used-near-albany-mo-to-escape.html Schoolboy stabs teacher], ''[[The New York Times]] (January 27, 1899)</ref>\n|}\n\n===1900s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=78width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| September 15, 1900\n| [[Kharkiv]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| Iwanow\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| After failing an exam, [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] student Iwanow shot and killed principal Tschanowitsch with a revolver, and also wounded a teacher named Horkiwicz, before surrendering to police.<ref>[http://dza.tessmann.it/tessmannPortal/Zeitungsarchiv/Seite/Zeitung/1/4/16.09.1900/43021/5 Die Rache des Gymnasiasten], ''Meraner Zeitung'' (September 16, 1900)</ref>\n|-\n| April 28, 1902\n| [[Kingston, Ontario]], Canada\n| Eric Sharp, 15\n| 1 dead\n| \n| Beatrice Holland, a 14-year-old student, is shot and killed by a fellow student at the Frontenac School. The shooter, 15-year-old Eric Sharp, fled the scene, but later turned himself in to the police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=nUouAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tX4FAAAAIBAJ&pg=6854,2114367&dq=school+tragedy&hl=en |title=Shot By Schoolmate Frontenac School, Kingston, Scene of a Tragedy. Boy Killed Girl Pupil |publisher=News.google.ca |date=1902-04-29 |accessdate=2017-10-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| February 24, 1903\n| [[Inman, South Carolina]], United States\n| Reuben Pitts\n| 1 dead\n| \n| Edward Foster, a 17-year-old student at Inman High school, was shot and fatally wounded by his teacher Reuben Pitts after he tried to resist punishment. Pitts said the student struck the pistol, which he drew in self-defense, and it fired. Pitts was acquitted of murder.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/ajc_historic/access/559912722.html?dids=559912722:559912722&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&date=Feb+25%2C+1903&author=&pub=The+Atlanta+Constitution&desc=CAROLINA+YOUTH+SHOT+BY+TEACHER&pqatl=google Carolina youth shot by teacher], ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'' (February 25, 1903)</ref><ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/ajc_historic/access/560490212.html?dids=560490212:560490212&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&date=Sep+20%2C+1903&author=&pub=The+Atlanta+Constitution&desc=REUBEN+PITTS+GETS+FREEDOM&pqatl=google Reuben Pitts gets freedom], ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'' (September 20, 1903)</ref>\n|-\n|July 21, 1903\n|[[Jackson, Kentucky]], United States\n|\n| 2 dead\n| 1 injured\n|At Cave Run School, James Barrett and Mack Howard fought a duel with pistols over a card game, killing each other. Another student James Vires, aged 12, suffered a wound while sitting at his desk.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cdnc/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&cl=search&d=LAH19030722.2.14&srpos=1&e=20-07-1903-22-07-1903--en--20-LAH-1--txt-IN-barrett----|work=Los Angeles Herald, Volume XXX, Number 288|title=Deulists Fatally Shot|date=22 July 1903}}</ref>\n|-\n|April 6, 1904\n|[[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States\n| Henry Schaze\n|1 dead\n|\n|Two students had been fighting over a girl for the better part of a year. Finally, Henry Schaze pushed 16-year-old Paul Jelick to the ground and shot him dead.<ref>''San Francisco Call,'' Volume 95, Number 129, 7 April 1904</ref>\n|-\n|November 16, 1904\n|[[Riverside, California]], United States\n|\n| 2 dead\n| 1 injured\n|At Indian School, a gun fight broke out between pupils. Charles Colby was shot in the head, then returned fire, killing Tom Bucanoros and fatally wounding Fred Smith.<ref>''San Francisco Call,'' Volume 96, Number 170, 17 November 1904</ref>\n|-\n|December 16, 1904\n|[[Magee, Mississippi]], United States\n| E. E. Mangum\n|1 dead\n|1 injured\n|E. E. Mangum was shot through the head and killed by the principal of the high school, Professor J. E. Woodward, after the student argued about punishment of his son and the argument became violent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cdnc/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&cl=search&d=SFC19041217.2.76.22&srpos=1&e=15-12-1904-17-12-1904--en--20-SFC-1--txt-IN-mangum----|work=San Francisco Call, Volume 97, Number 17|title=High School Principal Shoots Irate Parent|date=17 December 1904}}</ref>\n|-\n|February 9, 1905\n|[[Colusa, California]], United States\n|William Ingrim\n| \n|2 injured\n|At the request of his childhood friend, Pearl Cruse, Elmer Hildreth - a 17-year-old non-student, attended a meeting between Miss Cruse and her teacher. This meeting ended ended in \"a hand to hand\" encounter between the teacher and Cruse. Hildreth became involved in a physical confrontation with school trustee Ingrim, whom he shot. He was found to have acted in self-defense. Ingrim survived the shooting.<ref>''Colusa Sun Herald'' 15 February 1905</ref>\n|-\n| September 12, 1905\n| [[Athens, Tennessee]], United States\n| Ernest Powers, 15\n| 1 dead\n| \n| 15-year-old student Ernest Powers fatally stabbed his teacher Elbert Wattanbarger, when he attempted to whip him for throwing stones.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1905/09/17/archives/surrender-boy-who-slew-teacher.html Surrender Boy Who Slew Teacher], ''The New York Times'' (September 17, 1905)</ref>\n|-\n\n| April 15, 1908\n| [[Asheville, North Carolina]], United States\n| Dr. Curtis O. Swinney\n| 2 dead\n| \n| Dr. Curtis O. Swinney shot and fatally wounded his 16-year-old daughter Nellie in a reception room at Normal and Collegiate Institute. He was reported to be mad at her for a harmless April Fools prank she had played at school. He then committed suicide by shooting himself in the head.<ref>[https://tidingsofyore.wordpress.com/2013/04/01/father-kills-teenage-daughter-then-suicides-after-april-fools-day-prank/| Father Kills Teenage Daughter, Then Suicides After April Fools\u2019 Day Prank], ''The Manning Times'' (April 22, 1908)</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===1910s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| March 10, 1910\n| [[Ione, California]], United States\n| Albert Brown<br>Eugene Griffin\n|\n|\n| At the reform school, [[Preston School of Industry]], students Albert Brown and Eugene Griffin tried to escape after stealing a revolver from the school. They shot at Captain William H. White who pursued them. No one was hurt, but the two boys were transferred to the state penitentiary.<ref>''Amador Ledger,'' 11 March 1910</ref>\n|-\n| September 23, 1912\n| [[Sankt P\u00f6lten]], [[Austria]]\n| Rudolf Hlawat\n| 1 dead\n| \n| Rudolf Hlawat, a student at a [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] in St. P\u00f6lten, shot at his teacher, Prof. Schmidt, with a revolver. He also shot at the school janitor before shooting himself twice in the head. Hlawat died in hospital, the only casualty.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nzg&datum=19120924&seite=2&zoom=2 Revolverattentat eines Gymnasiasten auf den Professor], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (September 24, 1912)</ref>\n|-\n| October 9, 1913\n| [[Szeged]], [[Hungary]]\n| Johann Skultety, 14\n| 1 dead\n| \n| After he had been reprimanded by his teacher, Prof. Horvarth, for missing classes, Johann Skultety, a gymnasium student in Szeged, barged into his classroom and fired with a revolver at the teacher, missing him. He committed suicide by shooting himself in the heart.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nzg&datum=19131010&seite=3&zoom=2 Ein Revolverattentat eines Gymnasiasten auf seinen Professor], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (October 10, 1913)</ref>\n|-\n| April 12, 1919\n| [[Ogden City, Utah]], United States\n| \n| \n|1 injured\n|During a high school assembly, six boys shot off their guns, with permission, thinking they were loaded with blanks. Teacher Miss Verna Davidson was shot in the foot.<ref>''The Ogden Standard,'' April 26, 1919</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===1920s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n|February 14, 1920\n|[[Durant, Oklahoma]], United States\n|\n| \n|1 injured\n|At Durant Normal School, teacher Albert McFarland was shot and seriously wounded by one of his pupils.<ref>''The Daily Ardmoreite'' (Ardmore, Okla.), February 15, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|March 4, 1920\n|[[Cincinnati, Ohio]], United States\n| Lawrence Angel, 14\n| \n| 1 injured\n|A student, 14-year-old Lawrence Angel, shot his teacher Beatrice Conner through the arm for sending him to the principal's office.<ref>''The Bismarck Tribune'' (Bismarck, N.D.), March 04, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|March 12, 1920\n|[[Newberry, South Carolina]], United States\n|William Scott\n| \n|1 injured\n|William Scott, a student at Helena Colored School, shot Henry Gray, another student.<ref>''The Herald and News''', (Newberry S.C.), March 12, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|May 1, 1920\n|[[Summerville, Georgia]], United States\n|Alexander Potter, 15\n| \n|\n|At the High School, a student, 15-year-old Alexander Potter, fired six shots at his teacher, Prof. Ransom, but missed, upset after a severe thrashing. Potter was sentenced to 6 years at a reform school.<ref>The Watchman and Southron.(Sumter, S.C.), May 05, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|November 4, 1920\n|[[Middlesboro, Kentucky]], United States\n| Adolphus Oaks\n| 1 dead\n|\n|Prof. Barnes of Middlesboro High School was fatally shot by Adolphus Oaks, for whipping his sister the week before. Oaks went to jail.<ref>''The Ogden Standard-Examiner'' (Ogden, Utah), November 05, 1920</ref>\n|-\n| May 6, 1925\n| [[Wilno]], Poland\n| Two to three students\n| 5+ dead\n| ~10 injured\n| [[Wilno school massacre]]. A massacre occurred at [[Joachim Lelewel]] High School in [[Wilno]], [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]. At about 11 a.m., during the final exams, at least two eighth-grade students attacked the board of examiners with revolvers and hand grenades, killing at least one teacher, several students and themselves. An investigation revealed that the students had established a Communist youth organisation to counter the principal's strict management of the school. The members of this organisation had met the day before the exams in a tavern, to discuss the actions. <ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nfp&datum=19250507&seite=1&zoom=2 Revolversch\u00fcsse und Bombenw\u00fcrfe gegen Lehrer], ''[[Neue Freie Presse]]'' (May 7, 1925)</ref><ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0A16FF3B5B12738DDDAE0894DD405B858EF1D3 Bomb Kills Three Boy Raiders Who Shoot Up Vilna School], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (May 7, 1925)</ref>\n|-\n| May 18, 1927\n| [[Bath, Michigan]], United States\n| [[Andrew Kehoe]], 55\n| 45\n| 58\n| [[Bath School disaster]]. School board member [[Andrew Kehoe]] set up a series of explosions in the [[Bath Consolidated School]].  Before blowing up the school, Kehoe murdered his wife and set fire to his farmhouse.  After the bombings, Kehoe detonated his shrapnel-filled vehicle outside the school, committing suicide and wounding others. The bombings constitutes the deadliest act of mass murder in any type of school setting in U.S. history.\n|}\n\n===1930s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| March 5, 1931\n| [[Pristina]], [[Yugoslavia]]\n|\n|\n| 1 injured\n| A student named Ismailovic shot and stabbed his teacher several times at a gymnasium in Pristina after he had been expelled due to low grades. Ismailovic was later arrested at a cemetery when he tried to hang himself.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nzg&datum=19310306&seite=5&zoom=2 Die Rache eines durchgefallenen Gymnasiasten], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (March 6, 1931)</ref>\n|-\n| September 14, 1934\n| [[Gill, Massachusetts]], United States\n|\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Headmaster Elliott Speer was murdered by a shotgun blast through the window of his study at [[Northfield Mount Hermon School]]. The crime was never solved.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,848774,00.html |title=Education: Berkshire Mystery |publisher=Time.com |date=1937-06-07 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| September 24, 1937\n| [[Toledo, Ohio]], United States\n| Robert Snyder, 12\n|\n| 2 injured\n| 12-year-old Robert Snyder shot and wounded his principal, June Mapes, in her office at Arlington public school when she declined his request to call a classmate. He later shot and wounded himself but survived.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SO4KAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z08DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4212,6557992&dq= Lay shooting to gang tales], ''Prescott Evening Courier'' (September 24, 1937)</ref>\n|-\n| June 24, 1939\n| Tirpan, Bulgaria\n| ..., 15\n| 4 dead\n| \n| A 15-year-old student killed three teachers with a revolver at a school in Tirpan, southern Bulgaria after being expelled. The boy, who had already been expelled from three other schools during the year for bad behaviour, afterwards committed suicide.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1817&dat=19390625&id=xec-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=KU0MAAAAIBAJ&pg=5076,7768567 Boy kills teachers], ''[[The Tuscaloosa News]]'' (June 25, 1939)</ref><ref>[http://www.wbc.poznan.pl/dlibra/plain-content?id=118487 Ucze\u0144 zastrzeli\u0142 nauczycielk\u0119 i pope\u0142ni\u0142 samob\u00f3jstwo], ''[[Or\u0119downik Wrzesi\u0144ski]]'' (July 4, 1939)</ref>\n|}\n\n===1940s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| May 6, 1940\n| [[South Pasadena, California]], United States\n| Verlin Spencer, 38\n| 5 dead\n| 2 injured\n| After being removed as principal of South Pasadena Junior High School, Verlin Spencer shot six school officials, killing five, before attempting to commit suicide by shooting himself in the stomach. He was sentenced to five consecutive life sentences, and was released early on parole in 1970.<ref>[http://fultonhistory.com/Process%20small/Newspapers/Oswego%20Palladium/Oswego%20Palladium%20May-June%201940%20pdf/Newspaper%20%20Oswego%20Palladium%20May-June%201940%20-%200085.pdf 4 dead, 3 dying from gunfire of ousted educator, ''Oswego Palladium-Times''] (May 7, 1940)</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1940/05/10/archives/5-dead-in-school-killings-teacher-at-pasadena-succumbs-slayer-in.html 5 dead in school killings], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (May 10, 1940)</ref>\n|-\n| May 23, 1940\n|[[New York City, New York]], United States\n| Matthew Gillespie, 62\n|\n| 1 injured\n| Infuriated by a personal grievance, Matthew Gillespie, 62-year-old janitor at the junior school of the Dwight School for Girls, shot and critically wounded Mrs. Marshall Coxe, secretary of the junior school.\n|-\n| July 4, 1940\n|[[Valhalla, New York]], United States\n| Joseph Moshell, 47\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| Angered by the refusal of his daughter, 15-years-old Melba Moshell, to leave a boarding school in Valhalla and return to his home in Philadelphia, Joseph Moshell, 47, visited the school and shot and killed the girl. The girl had previously expressed fear of her father.  He then shot himself, but survived his injuries.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1940/07/05/archives/father-slays-girl-in-boarding-school-episcopal-nun-in-westchester.html| FATHER SLAYS GIRL IN BOARDING SCHOOL; Episcopal Nun in Westchester Sees Man Shoot Daughter, Who Feared Him, and Himself] |''[[The New York Times]]'' (July 5, 1940)</ref>\n|-\n| October 2, 1942\n| [[New York City, New York]], United States\n| Joseph Annunziata, 19 <br> Neil Simonelli, 16\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Joseph Annunziata and Neil Simonelli shot and killed teacher Irwin Goodman at William J. Gaynor Junior High School, after he had caught them smoking in a washroom. Neither Annunziata nor Simonelli was a student at the school.<ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0F15F83458167B93C1A9178BD95F468485F9 Two Boys Kill Teacher in School After 'Showing Off' by Smoking], ''The New York Times'' (October 3, 1942)</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nr4KAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w00DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5146,4095599&dq= Murder in a zoot suit], ''[[The Deseret News]]'' (October 10, 1942)</ref>\n|-\n| May 28, 1943\n| [[Brownsville, Pennsylvania]], United States\n| Thomas Celestine, 16\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 16-year-old Ettra Cimagha was stabbed to death by 16-year-old Thomas Celestine during a fight at Brownsville Junior High School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8jcxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AWoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2169,3353986&dq=school+stabbing+death&hl=en |title=Schoolboy Is Stabbed To Death In Scuffle |publisher=News.google.ca |date=1943-05-29 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n|June 26, 1946\n|[[New York City, New York]], United States\n|\n| \n|1 injured\n|A 15-year-old student who balked at turning over his pocket money to a gang of seven youths was shot in the chest at Public School 147 annex of the Brooklyn High School for Automotive Trades.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/06/26/archives/boy-in-school-shot-robbed-by-7-thugs-gang-of-youths-also-attempts.html|work=The New York Times|title=Boy In School Shot, Robbed by 7 Thugs|date=Jun 26, 1946}}</ref>\n|-\n| June 6, 1947\n| [[King William, Virginia]], United States\n| Robert Edward Lee, 20\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 17-year-old Linwood Johnson Regensburg was stabbed to death by 20-year-old Robert Edward Lee at a dance held at King William High School. Neither Regensburg nor Lee was a student at the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pxARAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1ooDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1317,6444103&dq=school+stabbing&hl=en |title=Youth Held In Fatal Stabbing |publisher=News.google.ca |date=1947-06-09 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===1950s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| July 22, 1950\n| [[New York City, New York]], United States\n|\n| \n| 1 injured\n| A 16-year-old boy was shot in the wrist and abdomen at a Public School 141 dance during an argument with a former classmate.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/07/22/archives/student-shot-at-dance-classmate-is-seized-on-school-roofvictim-in.html|work=The New York Times|title=Student Shot at Dance|date=Jul 22, 1950}}</ref>\n|-\n| January 24, 1951\n| [[Alton, Illinois]], United States\n| ..., 17\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Henry Suhre, 61, quartermaster at [[Western Military Academy]], was shot to death in the cadet store on campus. A 17-year-old cadet was arrested.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NV9HAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4P4MAAAAIBAJ&pg=3826,1959681&dq=killed+at+school&hl=en|work=Meriden Record|title=Academy Employee Killed On Campus|date=January 25, 1961}}</ref>\n|-\n| March 12, 1951\n| [[Union Mills, North Carolina]], United States\n| Billy Ray Powell, 16,<br>Hugh Justice, 19\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Professor W. E. Sweatt, superintendent and teacher at the Alexander School, was shot to death by students Billy Ray Powell, 16, and Hugh Justice, 19.  The assailants had been reprimanded by Sweatt, and accosted him outside his office.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Repository/TWH/1951/03/13/035-TWH-1951-03-13-001-SINGLE.pdf#OLV0_Entity_0001_0007|work=The Winona Republican-Herald|title=2 Youths Held in Slaying of Teacher, Chum|page=1|date=Mar 13, 1951|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202082124/http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Repository/TWH/1951/03/13/035-TWH-1951-03-13-001-SINGLE.pdf#OLV0_Entity_0001_0007|archivedate=2016-02-02}}</ref>\n|-\n| June 4, 1951\n| [[New York City, New York]], United States\n| \n| 1 dead\n|\n| Carl Arch, a 50-year-old intruder to a girls' gym class, was shot and killed by a police officer at Manhattan's Central Commercial High School.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1951/06/05/archives/policemans-shot-kills-crazed-man-who-invades-46th-st-girls-school.html|work=The New York Times|title=Crazed Man Killed in Girls' School|date=Jun 5, 1951}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 27, 1951\n| [[New York City, New York]], United States\n|\n| 1 dead\n|\n| David Brooks, a 15-year-old student, was fatally shot by two former students, as fellow pupils looked on in a grade school.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1951/11/27/archives/st-louis-pupil-killed-two-former-students-sought-in-grade-school.html?sq=%2522a+15+year+old+student%2522&scp=2&st=p|work=The New York Times|title=St. Louis Pupil Killed|date=Nov 27, 1951}}</ref>\n|-\n| April 9, 1952\n| [[New York City, New York]], United States\n| ..., 15\n| \n| 1 injured\n| A 15-year-old boarding school student shot a dean rather than relinquish pin-up pictures of girls in bathing suits.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1952/04/09/archives/dean-shot-over-pinups-georgia-student-15-refused-to-give-up.html?sq=%2522a+15+year+old%2522&scp=2&st=p|work=The New York Times|title=Dean Shot Over Pin Ups|date=Apr 9, 1952}}</ref>\n|-\n| September 3, 1952\n| [[Lawrenceville, Illinois]], United States\n| Charles Petrach, 25\n| 1 dead\n| \n| After 25-year-old Mildred Georgine Lyon ended her engagement with Charles Petrach, Petrach shot and killed Lyon in a classroom at Lawrenceville High School where she worked as a librarian. Charles Petrach was sentenced to 150 years in prison for the murder. A further stipulation to the sentence ordered that Patrach spend each September 3rd, the anniversary of the crime, in solitary confinement. However, on August 24 1967, Charles Petrach was released from prison, after serving only 15 years for the murder. <ref>http://lawrencelore.blogspot.com/2013/10/a-ghost-story-continued.html</ref><ref>http://sites.rootsweb.com/~ilavcem/lawrence_crime/lyon_georgine.htm</ref>\n|-\n| December 8, 1953\n| [[Aledo, Illinois]], United States\n| James Gipson, 17\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 26-year-old track coach George Marich was stabbed to death by 17-year-old student James Gipson in a hallway of Aledo High School. The stabbing occurred after Marich had removed Gipson and two other seniors from a study hall for creating a disturbance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HogRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uOIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5044,3631904&dq=james+gipson+george+marich&hl=en |title=Youth Stabs Track Coach |publisher=News.google.ca |date=1953-12-09 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| April 17, 1956\n| [[New York City, New York]], United States\n| Randolph Lawrence, 16\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 18-year-old Henry Smith, a student at a Bronx vocational high school, is stabbed to death by 16-year-old Randolph Lawrence, a fellow student. The stabbing was reportedly over a dispute about a [[basketball]] game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CZsSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xfYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4087,1300425&dq=school+stabbing&hl=en |title=Bronx Youth Killed in Fight at School |publisher=News.google.ca |date=1956-04-17 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| May 4, 1956\n| [[Prince George's County, Maryland]],\nUnited States\n| Billy Ray Prevatte, 15\n| 1 dead\n| 2 injured\n| 15-year-old student Billy Prevatte fatally shot one teacher and injured two other persons at Maryland Park Junior High School in [[Prince George's County, Maryland|Prince George's County]], after he had been suspended from the school.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/121280833.html?dids=121280833:121280833&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=MAY+05%2C+1956&author=&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=Billy+Seemed+'Nice+Boy'&pqatl=google Billy Seemed \"Nice Boy\"], [''[[The Washington Post]]''] (May 5, 1956)</ref>\n|-\n| October 20, 1956\n| [[New York City, New York]], United States\n|\n|\n| 1 injured\n| A Booker T. Washington Junior High School student was wounded in the forearm by another student armed with a home-made weapon.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/10/20/archives/monitor-shot-in-school-boy-14-wounded-by-bullet-from-homemade.html?sq=weapon&scp=1&st=p|work=The New York Times|title=Monitor Shot In School|date=Oct 20, 1956}}</ref>\n|-\n| October 2, 1957\n| [[New York City, New York]], United States\n| \n|\n| 1 injured\n| A 16-year-old student was shot in the leg by a 15-year-old classmate at a city high school.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/10/02/archives/boy-shot-in-east-side-school-christenberry-speeds-to-scene-gop.html?sq=shot&scp=7&st=p|work=The New York Times|title=Boy Shot In East Side School|date=Oct 2, 1957|first=Murray|last=Illson}}</ref>\n|-\n| March 4, 1958\n| [[New York City, New York]], United States\n| \n| \n| 1 injured\n| A 17-year-old student shot a boy in the Manual Training High School.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/03/06/archives/70000-bail-is-set-for-8-in-shooting.html?sq=%2522Manual+Training+High+School%2522&scp=1&st=p|work=The New York Times|title=$70,000 Bail Is Set For 8 In Shooting|date=Mar 6, 1958}}</ref>\n|-\n| May 1, 1958\n| [[Massapequa, New York]], United States\n| Bruce Zator, 15\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 15-year-old freshman Timothy Wall is shot to death by classmate Bruce Zator in a washroom of [[Massapequa High School]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Roy R. Silver (Special to The New York Times). |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0F10FE3C59107B93C3A9178ED85F4C8585F9 |title=Massapequa boy slain in school; Ambushed in Washroom \u2013 Classmate, 15, Confesses and Re-enacts Crime |publisher=Select.nytimes.com |date=1958-05-01 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| March 16, 1959\n| [[Edmonton, Alberta]], Canada\n| Stan Williamson, 19\n| 1 dead\n| 5 injured\n| 19-year-old Stan Williamson opened fire with a rifle inside [[Ross Sheppard High School]], killing 16-year-old Howard Gates and wounding five teenage girls. Three 18-year-old students tackled the gunman and held him down until he could be arrested by police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fL9UAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-jsNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4550,2676035&dq=school+shooting&hl=en |title=High school gun spree kills one, wounds five |publisher=News.google.ca |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| September 21, 1959\n| [[New York, New York]], United States\n| Unknown gunman\n| 1 dead\n| \n| A teenage boy was shot and killed at Morris High School. This was suspected to be related to gang activity. On September 23-24, police arrested twenty-seven men and boys and confiscated all of their weapons. Police suspected these men were members of multiple disparate gangs, which had been gathering weapons in anticipation of the start of a gang war over the murder. The prospective gang war was headed off by this seizure before it began. <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1959/09/24/archives/27-seized-in-bronx-with-gang-arsenal-27-seized-with-gang-arsenal-as.html |title= 27 Seized in Bronx With Gang Arsenal; 27 Seized With Gang Arsenal As Fight in Bronx Is Blocked |work=New York Times|date= September 24, 1959}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===1960s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| March 30, 1960\n| [[Alice, Texas]], United States\n| Donna Dvorak, 14\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Donna Dvorak, 14, brought a target pistol to Dubose Junior High School, and fatally shot Bobby Whitford, 15, in their 9th grade science class.  Dvorak believed Whitford posed a threat to one of her girlfriends.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jthHAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IoAMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3467,122520&dq=dvorak&hl=en|work=The Victoria Advocate|title=Youth Fatally Shot In Crowded Class|date=Mar 31, 1960}}</ref>\n|-\n| March 4, 1961\n| [[Kung\u00e4lv]], [[Sweden]] \n| Ove Conry Andersson, 17\n| 1 dead\n| 6 injured\n| |[[Kung\u00e4lv school shooting]]. A 17-year-old student fired fifteen bullets into a crowd at a school dance at Kung\u00e4lvs L\u00e4roverk (a/k/a Thorildskolan), killing one student and wounding six others before escaping. He turned himself in to local police the following morning and was arrested.\n|-\n| October 17, 1961\n| [[Denver, Colorado]], United States\n| Tennyson Beard, 14\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| Tennyson Beard, 14, got into an argument with William Hachmeister, 15, at Morey Junior High School. During the argument Beard pulled out a revolver and shot at Hachmeister, wounding him. Deborah Faith Humphrey, 14, was fatally wounded by another shot. Beard was arrested after fleeing the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PAozAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w-cDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4617,710365 |title=School Fight Mushrooms Into Murder |publisher=News.google.com |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| January 26, 1962\n| [[Taipei]], [[Taiwan]]\n| Tsui Yin, 41\n| 7 dead\n| 3 injured\n| Tsui Yin, a 41-year-old former physical education teacher at Li Shing Junior High School in Taipei, shot and killed the principal, the principal's wife and five other faculty members with a pistol, in revenge for his dismissal. He wounded three others, among them the principal's daughter, before escaping in a taxi. He was arrested and sentenced to death.<ref>Admits killing 7 for revenge, ''[[Pacific Stars and Stripes]]'' (January 27, 1962)</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=H2gUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KQEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7282,775520&dq= Teacher who slew 7 denied wish to see pupil perform], ''[[Toledo Blade]]'' (July 26, 1962)</ref>\n|-\n|May 7, 1963\n|[[Paterson, New Jersey]]\n|Ralph Best, 43\n|\n|6 injured\n|Gun engraver Ralph Best opened fire from his second floor room with a .22 caliber hunting rifle on 50 children playing in the schoolyard at Paterson School 14, on the evening of May 7, 1963. An alcoholic and epileptic, he fired after the children ignored his demands they leave the playground. Charged with \"atrocious assault\", Best pled insanity. His first trial ended in a mistrial, and he was never re-tried.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.northjersey.com|title=An oft-forgotten school shooting|last=Maag|first=Christopher|date=January 21, 2019|work=The Record|access-date=|page=1A}}</ref>\n|-\n| April 27, 1966\n| [[Bay Shore, New York]], United States\n| James Arthur Frampton, 16\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Teacher John S. Lane, 48, was shot and fatally wounded when he tried to stop 16-year-old student James Arthur Frampton, who was walking with a shotgun in the high school, seeking students with whom he had argued. Lane died of his wounds on June 13, 1966.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1966/04/28/archives/li-teacher-shot-by-boy-in-school-badly-wounded-trying-to-halt.html L.I. teacher shot by boy in school], ''The New York Times'' (April 28, 1966)</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1966/04/29/archives/li-boy-held-in-shooting-faces-psychiatric-exam.html L.I. Boy Held in Shooting Faces Psychiatric Exam], ''The New York Times'' (April 29, 1966)</ref><ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0B1FFD3559137B93C6A8178DD85F428685F9 Teacher Shot by Youth Dies in Bay Shore Hospital], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (June 14, 1966)</ref>\n|-\n| October 5, 1966\n| [[Grand Rapids, Minnesota]], United States\n| David M. Black Jr., 15\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| David Black, a 15-year-old student at [[Grand Rapids High School]], took a pistol to school - shooting student Kevin Roth and administrator Forrest L. Willey, with whom he had argued. Willey died of his wound eight days later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbine-angels.com/grand_rapids_high.htm |title=A wound still fresh//The survivor of a 1966 school shooting in Minnesota is still coming to grips with the pain \u2013 and with his own role in the tragedy |publisher=Columbine-angels.com |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| September 26, 1967\n| [[Dayton, Ohio]], United States\n| Will Edward Dixon, 19\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Thomas Prinz, a 21-year-old football coach at Wilbur Wright High School, was stabbed to death by 19-year-old Will Edward Dixon. The stabbing occurred when Prinz attempted to escort Dixon off the playing field. Dixon was a former student and drop-out from the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iJYuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IUgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5062,4240840&dq=school+stabbing+death&hl=en |title=Dayton Coach Stabbed To Death By Youth |publisher=News.google.ca |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 1, 1967\n| [[Dundee]], [[Scotland]], United Kingdom\n| [[Robert Mone]], 19\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 19-year-old soldier Robert Mone entered [[St John's RC High School]] armed with a shotgun and took a class hostage. He sexually abused the children. The teacher, Nanette Hanson, convinced Mone, who had already raped one girl, to let the children go. Mone fatally shot her in the head. Mone had been expelled three years before, and was apparently seeking revenge; he was found to be insane and sent to the [[State Hospital]] in [[Carstairs]].<ref>[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/2007/11/02/tribute-to-teacher-killed-by-monster-mone-86908-20049591/ Tribute To Teacher Killed By Monster Mone], ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' (November 2, 2007)</ref>\n|-\n| January 30, 1968\n| [[Miami]], [[Florida]], United States\n| Blanche Patricia Ward, 16\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 16-year-old Blanche Ward shot and killed fellow 16-year-old student, Linda Lipscomb, with a pistol at Miami Jackson High School. According to Ward, she was threatened with a razor by Lipscomb during an argument and in the ensuing struggle her gun went off.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vBoMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vlwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4031,176485&dq= Fatal shooting brings action], ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'' (February 1, 1968)</ref>\n|-\n| March 25, 1968\n| [[High Point, North Carolina]],  United States\n| Gerald Locklear, 16\n| 1 dead\n| \n| David Walker, 15, was shot to death just outside Central High School by Gerald Locklear, 15.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19680326&id=j7VWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gOkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5447,3659292&hl=en Student Held In Slaying], ''[[The Spokesman-Review]]'' (March 26, 1968)</ref>\n|-\n| May 22, 1968\n| [[Miami]], [[Florida]], United States\n| Ernest Lee Grissom, 15\n|\n| 2 injured\n| Ernest Lee Grissom, a 15-year-old student at Drew Junior High School, shot and seriously wounded a teacher and a 13-year-old student after he had been reprimanded for a disturbance.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=i-MTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SQUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2587,3245401&dq= Teacher, student serious following shooting by youth], ''[[Ocala Star-Banner]]'' (May 23, 1968)</ref>\n|-\n| January 23, 1969\n| [[Washington, District of Columbia]], United States\n| Ronald Joyner, 18\n| 1 dead\n|\n| [[Cardozo Senior High School]] assistant principal Herman Clifford, 45, was shot to death in the hallway by Ronald Joyner, 18, while scuffling with three youths who robbed the school's bank.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/01/25/archives/principals-aide-in-capital-is-killed-chasing-thieves.html?sq=%2522Clifford%2522&scp=16&st=p|work=The New York Times|title=Principal's Aide in Capital is Killed Chasing Thieves|date=Jan 25, 1969}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 19, 1969\n| [[Tomah, Wisconsin]], United States\n| ..., 14\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Principal Martin Mogensen is shot to death in his office by a 14-year-old boy armed with a [[shotgun]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.madison.com/wsj/spe/Weston/index.php?ntid=101225 |title=Some other incidents involving guns at Wisconsin schools |publisher=Madison.com |date=2011-02-15 |accessdate=2011-03-12 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19691120&id=JUIVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HAgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5900,1913651 |title=Shots Kill High School Principal |publisher=News.google.com |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===1970s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| January 5, 1970\n| [[Washington, District of Columbia]], United States\n| Unnamed student\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| Tyrone Perry, 15, was shot to death and a 14-year-old boy was wounded at Hine Junior High School.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AfRYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cOsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3025,1894998&dq=boy+shot+at+school&hl=en|work=The Spokesman-Review|title=Boys Hurt, Killed In Shootings|date=January 6, 1970}}</ref>\n|-\n| February 1, 1971\n| [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], United States\n| Kevin Simmons, 14\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Samson L. Freedman, a 56-year-old art teacher, was shot to death by Kevin Simmons at Leeds Junior High School, after having the student suspended for cursing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/02/02/archives/art-teacher-slain-philadelphia-police-arrest-youth-14.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923170859/http://www.nytimes.com/1971/02/02/archives/art-teacher-slain-philadelphia-police-arrest-youth-14.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 September 2016|title=Art Teacher Slain; Philadelphia Police Arrest Youth, 14 \u2013 The New York Times|date=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 3, 1971\n| [[Carlsbad, New Mexico]],\nUnited States\n| Michael O'Hearn, 22\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| Michael O'Hearn barricaded himself in a storage tower of Carlsbad Mid-High School, in [[Carlsbad, New Mexico]], for about two hours with two firearms. He fired about two dozen rounds at police officers, injuring one, before committing suicide.<ref name=\"stpetersburg110471\">{{cite news|title=Sniper's Victim: Himself|date=1971-11-04|url =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=k9IMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tWADAAAAIBAJ&pg=3115,1900854&|work=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|accessdate = 2009-04-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| January 24, 1972\n| [[Stow, Ohio]], United States\n| \n|\n| 1 injured\n| A 16-year-old student at Stow High School shot and wounded his chemistry teacher during an argument.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dk8LAAAAIBAJ&sjid=a1IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5155,1313401&dq= Youth shoots chem teacher], ''[[The Bryan Times]]'' (January 25, 1972)</ref>\n|-\n| January 7\u201312, 1973\n| [[Balassagyarmat]], Hungary\n| Andr\u00e1s Pintye, 18 and L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Pintye, 17\n| 1 dead\n| Several hostages required medical attention\n| Brothers Andr\u00e1s and L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Pintye, sons of local Communist Party officials, have acquired a [[FEG PA-63|PA-63]] pistol and an [[AMD-65|AMD]] assault rifle and assaulted a local girls' dormitory. They held an unknown number of teenage girls hostage for several days, demanding free passage to Budapest's international airport and a flight to Austria. Finally, when they planned to murder some of the hostages, a police sniper shot Andr\u00e1s dead through the window, then the police stormed the building, arresting L\u00e1szl\u00f3. He was sentenced to 15 years of prison, from which he was released in 1984, serving a little more than 11 years. Four other persons were sentenced for aiding the perpetrators. The case deeply traumatized Hungary which has never seen such events before. A feature film titled T\u00faszt\u00f6rt\u00e9net (Hostage Story) was made about the events in 1989.<ref>[[:hu:Balassagyarmati t\u00faszdr\u00e1ma#A t.C3\u00baszdr\u00e1ma ut\u00f3\u00e9lete|Wikipedia (Hungarian) article about the hostage drama]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=May 2017}}\n|-\n| February 26, 1973\n| [[Richmond, Virginia]], United States\n|\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Wayne Phillips, 17, was shot to death when he was caught between two youths who were fighting in the hallway of [[Armstrong High School (Richmond, Virginia)|Armstrong High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CTJgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=s28NAAAAIBAJ&pg=4009,6506820&dq=boy+killed+at+school&hl=en |newspaper=The Phoenix|title=Boy Killed In Gun Battle|date=February 27, 1973}}</ref>\n|-\n| July 1973\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| In the [[attack on St Alberts School]], [[Zimbabwe African National Liberation Army]] (ZANLA) cadres captured 292 pupils and staff from the school and [[death march|force-marched]] them north towards [[Mozambique (Portugal)|Mozambique]], where the ZANLA bases were. The march was intercepted by the [[Rhodesian Security Forces]] before the cadres crossed the border, and all but eight of the children and staff were recovered.<ref>{{cite book|title=Counter-Insurgency in Rhodesia|last=Cilliers|first=Jackie|location=London, Sydney & Dover, New Hampshire|publisher=Croom Helm|date=December 1984|isbn=978-0-7099-3412-7|page=18}}</ref>\n|-\n| February 2, 1974\n| [[San Luca]], Italy\n|\n| 1 dead\n|\n| A student shot and killed his teacher, Silvio Strangio, after he had been reprimanded for distracting his classmates.<ref>[http://hemeroteca.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/madrid/abc/1974/02/03/033.html Mata a su profesor en clase], ''[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]'' February 3, 1974</ref>\n|-\n| March 22, 1974\n| [[Brownstown, Indiana]], United States\n| \n| 1 dead\n|\n| Jessie Blevins, 48, athletic director at Brownstown Central High School, was shot to death in the school parking lot by a 17-year-old student.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=W3dQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fxEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6244,1615348&dq=boy+killed+at+school&hl=en |newspaper=The Milwaukee Sentinel|title=Pupil Shoots, Kills Athletic Director|date=March 23, 1974}}</ref>\n|-\n| December 30, 1974\n| [[Olean, New York]], United States\n| Anthony Barbaro, 17\n| 3 dead\n| 11 injured\n| [[Olean High School shooting]]. 17-year-old student Anthony Barbaro indiscriminately shot at people on the street from windows at the third floor of the school building. He killed three people and wounded 11 before police managed to subdue him.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vQ4LAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-VEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3163,7727175&dq=anthony+barbaro+regent Teen sniper kills three, 11 wounded, ''The Bryan Times''] (December 31, 1974)</ref>\n|-\n| March 18, 1975\n| [[St. Louis, Missouri]], United States\n| \n| 1 dead\n| \n| 16-year-old Stephen Goods, a bystander, is shot and killed during a fight between other teens at [[Sumner High School (St. Louis)|Sumner High School]].<ref name=\"PAC\">{{cite web | url=http://policeacademyu.com/school-violence/ | title=Facts about school violence in the U.S. |publisher=policeacademyu.com | accessdate=December 12, 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214212942/http://policeacademyu.com/school-violence/ | archivedate=December 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| May 28, 1975\n| [[Brampton, Ontario]], Canada\n| Michael Slobodian, 16\n| 3 dead\n| 13 injured\n| [[Centennial Secondary School shooting]]. Michael Slobodian, 16, killed a teacher and student and wounded 13 others at Brampton Centennial Secondary School in Brampton, Ontario, before fatally shooting himself.\n|-\n| September 11, 1975\n| [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]], United States\n| James Briggs, 15\n| 1 dead\n| 5 injured\n| Grant High School student Randy Truitt was shot and killed by James Briggs at the school, who also wounded several others.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pFVOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yPgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3249%2C2241230 |title=Charge Filed in Shooting |work=[[Spokane Daily Chronicle]] |date=September 24, 1975 |accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| October 27, 1975\n| [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| [[Robert Poulin]], 18\n| 3 dead\n| 5 injured\n| [[St. Pius X High School shooting]]. 18-year-old Robert Poulin opened fire on his class with a shotgun at [[St. Pius X High School (Ottawa)|St. Pius X High School]], killing one and wounding five before turning the gun on himself. Poulin had raped and stabbed his 17-year-old friend Kim Rabot to death prior to the shooting.\n|-\n| February 12, 1976\n| [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], United States\n| \n| \n| 5 injured\n| Intruders shot five Murray-Wright High School students after an apparent dispute over one of the intruder's girlfriends.<ref name=wound5>\"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LQ9PAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dgIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3947,2156747&dq=murray-wright-high-school&hl=en Intruders Wound 5 Students In Shooting At Detroit School]\". ''[[Associated Press]]'' at the ''[[Toledo Blade]]''. Friday February 13, 1976 (141st year). Page 2. Retrieved from [[Google Books]] (3 of 20) on November 2, 2012.</ref>\n|-\n| April 7, 1977\n| [[Whitharral, Texas]], United States\n| Ricardo Lopez, 17\n| 1 dead\n|\n| High School principal M. O. Tripp was shot to death on the front steps of the school by Ricardo Lopez, 17.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=REAhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_1EDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5618,677358&dq=tripp&hl=en|work=The Bryan Times|title=Police Don't Know Reason Student Killed His Principal|date=Apr 7, 1977}}</ref>\n|-\n| December 12, 1977\n| [[Winter Garden, Florida]], United States\n| Roosevelt Holloman, 41\n| 1 dead\n|\n| During an after-school meeting at West Orange High School to discuss his illegal advances toward a 16-year-old girl, 41-year-old assistant principal Roosevelt Holloman pulled out a gun and shot principal Raymond Screws, 51, to death. Holloman also shot at two other school officials but missed. Holloman surrendered his gun to a janitor and waited until being arrested. He was later convicted of [[first-degree murder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=19771213&id=N-8LAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HVoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3129,4205065 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120723175746/http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=19771213&id=N-8LAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HVoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3129,4205065 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-23 |title=Principle (sic) shot to death |publisher=News.google.com |date=1977-12-13 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1346&dat=19771213&id=ZnUsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=o_oDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6331,2860961 |title=School Principle (sic) Shot to Death |publisher=News.google.com |date=1977-12-13 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5gMMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=g1oDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3946,830644&dq=principal+shot+screws+kissed&hl=en |title=Slayer of school principal convicted of first-degree murder |publisher=News.google.ca |date=1978-06-10 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| January 4, 1978\n| [[New York City, New York]], United States\n| Everton Lazarus, 16\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Michael Kittrell, 15, was stabbed to death by another student at John Adams High School.<ref>{{cite news|author=[ Displaying Abstract ] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/02/03/archives/youth-is-arrested-in-students-killing.html |title=Youth Is Arrested In Student's Killing |publisher=Select.nytimes.com |date=2011-03-02 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| February 22, 1978\n| [[Lansing, Michigan]], United States\n| Roger Needham, 15\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| Roger Needham, a 15-year-old student, shot two students at Everett High School. One of the students, 15-year-old Bill Draher, died of his gunshot wound.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kresnak |first=Jack |url=http://www.justicejournalism.org/crimeguide/chapter02/chapter02_pg02.html |title=Juvenile Justice |publisher=Justicejournalism.org |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| May 18, 1978\n| [[Austin, Texas]], United States\n| John Daniel Christian, 13\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 13-year-old honor student John Christian, son of former LBJ press secretary [[George Christian (journalist)|George Christian]], fatally shot his teacher, 29-year-old Rod Grayson, three times at Murchison Junior High School. Christian fled the school building and was subdued by gym coach Larry Schirpik. Christian's attorney, Roy Minton, argued Christian was [[Insanity defence|not guilty by reason of insanity]], and district attorney Ronnie Earle did not object. The case did not go to trial. Christian was treated for two years at a private mental health facility in Dallas paid for by his family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michaelcorcoran.net/archives/1469 |title=Austin\u2019s Secret: Killing in the Classroom 1978 |publisher=MichaelCorcoran.net |accessdate=2012-12-17}}</ref>\n|-\n| October 1978\n| [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]], Canada\n| Vaughan Pollen, 17\n| 1 dead\n|\n| A 16-year-old student, Kenneth Maitland, was shot to death with a shotgun by 17-year-old student, Vaughan Pollen, at Sturgeon Creek Regional Secondary School. Pollen was charged with murder but during the trial found unfit to stand trial by reason of a mental disorder. He was committed to a mental health facility for treatment of [[paranoid schizophrenia]] and treated for 7 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/school-shootings/ |title=Attacks on students and staff |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2008-09-23 |accessdate=2011-03-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100130091329/http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/school-shootings/ |archivedate=January 30, 2010 }}</ref>\n|-\n| January 29, 1979\n| [[San Diego, California]], United States\n| Brenda Spencer\n| 2 dead\n| 9 injured\n| A 16-year-old student, Brenda Spencer, began shooting from her home at children who were waiting outside Cleveland Elementary School for principal Burton Wragg (aged 53) to open the gates. She injured eight children. Wragg was killed while trying to help the children. Custodian Mike Suchar (aged 56) was killed while trying to pull a student to safety. Asked by a reporter why she committed the crime, Spencer is said to have replied \"[[I Don't Like Mondays]]\"\n|}\n\n===1980s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| January 7, 1980\n| [[Stamps, Arkansas]], United States\n| Evan Hampton, 16\n| 1 dead\n| \n| Evan Hampton, 16, high school freshman student at Stamps High School, shot Mike Sanders, 19, twice in the chest and once in the temple, killing him instantly. He was arrested.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=799&dat=19800109&id=0CccAAAAIBAJ&sjid=41cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6542,692754|newspaper=The Bryan Times|title=Death of student makes no sense|date=January 9, 1980}}</ref>\n|-\n| October 31, 1980\n| [[Hueytown, Alabama]], United States\n| Rudy Farmer, 17\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| 17-year-old Rudy Farmer pulled out a pistol and shot a fellow student in the art room at Hueytown High School.  That student was wounded.  Farmer fatally shot himself.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1454&dat=19801101&id=CcgsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RRMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6542,12997|newspaper=The Star-News|title=Student killed in school shooting|date=November 1, 1980}}</ref>\n|-\n| October 2, 1981\n| [[Greenville, South Carolina]], United States\n| Jewel Loraine Garrett, 18\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Henry Chiariello, a 30-year-old social studies teacher, was stabbed to death at Greenville High School by 18-year-old student Jewel Garrett. Garrett was later sentenced to life in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=KnQQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=m4sDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5899,421593&dq=henry+chiariello |title=Slain |publisher=News.google.com |date=1981-10-03 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| January 12, 1982\n| [[Miami, Florida]], United States\n| Steven Wayne Holmes, 15\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Francisco Walker, 24, a sixth-grade teacher at Edison Middle School, was stabbed to death by a teenaged trespasser, 15-year-old Steven Wayne Holmes. He was later arrested and charged with first degree murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kNMRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h-4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6038,4608633&dq=school+stabbing+death&hl=en |title=Teacher stabbed to death |publisher=News.google.ca |date=1982-01-13 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WOgTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EwYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5606,5408156&dq=francisco+walker&hl=en |title=15-Year-Old Arrested In Slaying Of Teacher |publisher=News.google.ca |date=1982-01-13 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| March 19, 1982\n| [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], United States\n| Pat Lizotte, 17\n| 1 dead\n| 3 injured\n| Clarence Piggott, a 55-year-old psychology and sociology teacher, was shot to death, and two students were wounded by a high school senior. The student was later shot and wounded by police before arrest.<ref>{{cite news|author=AP |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F30911FB3D5D0C738EDDAA0894DA484D81 |title=The New York Times Article March 20, 1982 |location=Las Vegas (Nev) |publisher=Select.nytimes.com |date=1982-03-20 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FLQSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YvkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6010,1797067&dq= Shooting spree], ''[[Spokane Chronicle]]'' (March 22, 1982)</ref> Lizotte is sentenced to two consecutive life sentences without the possibility of parole. However, he was granted parole on March 6, 2017 after a Nevada law banning life without parole for juveniles reduced his sentence to 20 years to life.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news3lv.com/news/local/student-convicted-in-1982-shooting-death-of-valley-hs-teacher-granted-parole|title=Student convicted in 1982 shooting death of Valley HS teacher granted parole|last=Garcia|first=John Treanor and Tony|work=KSNV|access-date=2017-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n| April 7, 1982\n| [[Littleton, Colorado]], United States\n| [[1982 Deer Creek Shooting|Jason Rocha]], 14\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Jason Rocha, a 14-year-old student, shot and killed 13 year-old Scott Darwin Michael, a fellow student at [[Deer Creek Middle School]] in Littleton, Colorado. Rocha was charged as an adult and sentenced to 12-years in prison for the murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19840304&id=U0IsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rM4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5024,759361 |title=These Kids Are \u2018Middle-Class Murderers |publisher=News.google.com |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| January 20, 1983\n| [[St. Louis County, Missouri]], United States\n| David F. Lawler, 14\n| 2 dead\n| 1 injured\n| 14-year-old David F. Lawler took two family pistols to school and shot two classmates, killing one and injuring the other. In a murders/suicide note he had brought with him, he outlined his intention to kill the next person heard speaking ill of his older brother Ken. He entered a study hall classroom and opened fire, hitting the two victims. The first was fatally shot in the stomach, and the second received a non-fatal gunshot wound to the abdomen. After, he said, \"no one will ever call my brother a pussy again\". He then committed suicide. See [[Parkway South Junior High School shooting|Parkway South Junior High School killings]] for more information.\n|-\n| May 16, 1983\n| [[Dallas, Texas]], United States\n| Billy Conn Gardner\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Billy Conn Gardner, a friend of a food service worker's husband, robbed the [[Lake Highlands High School]] cafeteria at gunpoint, shot the food service director, and left with $1,600. The food service director, Thelma Row, died eleven days later from the injuries. Gardner was later apprehended, convicted, and sentenced to death via Lethal Ejection for the crime. The State of Texas executed him on February 16, 1995.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://lakehighlands.advocatemag.com/2014/03/history-shooting-lake-highlands-cafeteria-worker-remembered/|author=Toler, Carol|title=History: Shooting of Lake Highlands cafeteria worker remembered|date=2014-03-04|accessdate=2018-04-26|publisher=Advocate Magazine (Lake Highlands)}}</ref>\n|-\n| June 3, 1983\n| [[Eppstein|Eppstein-Vockenhausen]], Germany\n| Karel Charva, 34\n| 6 dead\n| 14 injured\n| [[Eppstein school shooting]]. Thirty-five-year-old [[Czechs|Czech]] [[refugee]] Karel Charva, fatally shot three students, a teacher and a police officer, and injured another 14 people with two [[semi-automatic pistol]]s, before committing [[suicide]] at the [[Heinrich Friedrich Karl vom und zum Stein|Freiherr-vom-Stein]] [[Gesamtschule]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/04/world/around-the-world-classroom-gun-rampage-leaves-6-germans-dead.html Classroom Gun Rampage Leaves 6 Germans Dead], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (June 4, 1983)</ref>\n|-\n| December 16, 1983\n| [[Rockford, Illinois]], United States\n| Michael Graham, 15\n|\n| 1 injured\n| Michael Graham, a 15-year-old student at Boylan Central Catholic High School, shot and wounded his German teacher, Sharon Mundt, who had disciplined him for misbehavior.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uSEVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UwYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3636,1012288&dq= Student's threat to shoot teacher was dismissed by classmates as joke], ''[[Ocala Star-Banner]]'' (December 18, 1983)</ref>\n|-\n| March 13, 1984\n| [[Castres]], France\n| \n| 2 dead\n|\n| A 15-year-old student killed his teacher, who had sent him to the headmaster for being late, and shot himself in the head. He died on the way to the hospital.<ref>[http://suche.abendblatt.de:8000/article.php?xmlurl=http://87.230.59.37/ha/1984/xml/19840314xml/habxml840103_9060.xml&pdfurl=http://87.230.59.37/ha/1984/pdf/19840314.pdf/ASV_HAB_19840314_HA_032.pdf Lehrer erschossen]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''[[Hamburger Abendblatt]]'' (March 14, 1984)</ref>\n|-\n|March 29, 1985\n|[[Spartanburg, South Carolina|Spartanburg]], [[South Carolina]], United States\n|\n|\n|\n|A 15 year old freshman held four students [[hostage]] at [[Paul M. Dorman High School]], after leaving school grounds when being accused of drinking, and returning to the school with a loaded .38 Colt [[revolver]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goupstate.com/news/19990502/student-gunman-took-hostages-in-spartanburg-14-years-ago-it-happened-here|title=Student gunman took hostages in Spartanburg 14 years ago It happened here|last=PREVATTE|first=PAM|work=GoUpstate|access-date=2018-02-20|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|September 4, 1985\n|[[Richmond, Virginia]], United States\n| Student, 12-years-old\n| 1 dead\n|\n| At the end of the second day of school at East End Middle School, a 12-year-old boy shot a girl with his mother's gun. <ref> https://www.k12academics.com/school-shootings/history-school-shootings-united-states}</ref>\n|-\n| October 18, 1985\n| [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], United States\n| \n| \n| 6 injured\n| During halftime of the homecoming football game between [[Northwestern High School (Michigan)|Northwestern]] and [[Murray-Wright High School|Murray-Wright]], a boy who had been in a fight earlier that day retaliated with a shotgun, wounding six students.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]] |title=6 Shot, Injured at Homecoming|url=https://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl/1985_45387/6-shot-injured-at-homecoming.html}